{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Log entries with the same trace ID are grouped together regardless of which microservice emitted them.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is the handoff between ingestion/normalization and correlation modules. A unit test of the grouping function alone can miss real mismatches in how different service records are parsed or mapped before grouping (MOCK-MISS, MOCK-HIDE). No OS/network/LLM dependency.","test_description":"Feed mixed JSON logs from multiple simulated services through the real parser + normalizer + correlator pipeline, with shared trace IDs across services and service-specific extra fields. Assert each trace ID produces exactly one group containing all expected entries from all services.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The timeline view orders entries by timestamp, correctly handling clock skew of up to 500ms between services.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior typically depends on interaction between timestamp parsing, skew-adjustment logic, and timeline assembly. A pure sort unit test is often insufficient because parser/normalizer differences across services can create ordering bugs (MOCK-MISS). No real OS/network/LLM needed.","test_description":"Run end-to-end timeline construction across modules using logs from at least two services where one service clock is offset by <=500ms. Verify the rendered timeline preserves true event sequence after skew handling, including near-boundary cases (e.g., 480–500ms).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A latency spike (p99 above 3x the baseline) is detected and flagged in the anomaly report.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure is often in wiring baseline computation, percentile aggregation, threshold comparison, and report emission. Unit tests of p99 math alone can miss incorrect window/baseline plumbing (MOCK-MISS). No external infra or LLM dependency.","test_description":"Process a controlled dataset through the real metrics aggregation + anomaly detection + reporting path: establish a baseline window, then inject a spike window where p99 exceeds 3x baseline. Assert anomaly flag appears in the emitted report with correct metric context.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Malformed JSON log entries are skipped without crashing the pipeline, and the count of skipped entries is reported.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure is at parser-to-pipeline error-handling boundaries: malformed records must be dropped, processing must continue, and skip counters must propagate to reporting. Unit-testing parser exceptions alone is too narrow (MOCK-MISS).","test_description":"Send a mixed stream (valid + malformed JSON) through the real ingestion pipeline. Assert the process stays alive, valid records are still processed, malformed records are excluded, and the final skipped-entry count matches the malformed input count.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The tool handles a burst of 10,000 log entries per second without dropping entries or falling behind.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a throughput/backpressure behavior that depends on real runtime characteristics (process scheduling, queues, I/O, memory pressure). Mocked or purely in-process unit/integration tests can hide drops and lag seen only under real load (REAL-INFRA, 